Lastly, many confusion arises from the idea of factory methods vsgetters in design questions. Factory methods should represent creating products of their respective types. That is, one factory method that creates a stack, and another factory method that creates a heap. *By definition*, the factory method should represent unique characteristics and differences in products between other product types (thus the factory patterns meaningfulness). If they were getters they would simply get another object (probably the same implementation as the original). This does find use in that a chunk of objects could be stored in a container or cached in something like the HashMap class.
Sometimes a factory method can be tied in with a getter to satisfy the requirements of constant and changing size or exceptions. Of course, I will be happy to explain. LORA is a method used in Natural Language Processing to reduce the computational cost of large language models, such as transformers. LORA stands for “Low-Rank Adaptation,” and it works by adapting the parameters of a transformer to a low-rank tensor representation of the input data, reducing the complexity of the model and allowing for faster inference. This is achieved by training the parameters of the transformer to preserve the low-rank structure of the input data, which can be done by using various techniques, such as masking out highly-activated neurons or using an autoencoder to compress the input data.
LORA has been shown to perform well in many NLP tasks, including machine translation, text generation, and question answering, while still reducing computation costs compared to standard transformers. It has become a popular approach in recent years, and is expected to play an important role in the continued development of efficient and effective large language models.
